    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-06-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="45"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d45">
                <head>45. Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of State for Far Eastern Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_RWS1" type="from">Robertson</persName>) to the <gloss
                        type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d45fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 411.90B41/6–2556. Secret. Sent through Under Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName>, whose initials, indicating his
                        approval, appear on the source text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-06-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 25, 1956</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Economic Assistance to Burma</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Discussion:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The attached cables concern the reopening of economic assistance negotiations
                    with Burma (Tabs A, B and C<note n="2" xml:id="d45fn2">The tabs, not attached to
                        the source text, were telegrams 1305, 1306, and 1307 to Rangoon; <ref
                            target="#d47">Documents 47</ref>, <ref target="#d48">48</ref>, and <ref
                            target="#d49">49</ref>.</note>).</p>
                <p>On June 14, 1956 you indicated that a favorable response should be given to
                        <persName corresp="#p_NU1">U Nu</persName>’s request for grant assistance in
                    return for a token rice payment. You also noted that additional funds should not
                    be requested <pb facs="0101" n="73" xml:id="pg_73"/> quested but rather a sum of
                    $5 million for this purpose should be taken from the $25 million already
                    earmarked for dollar loans to Burma.</p>
                <p>In view of Congressional sentiment and the possibility that grant aid
                    appropriations may be seriously curtailed, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HJB1"
                        >Hollister</persName> has informed the Department of his reluctance to
                    commit any funds for additional grant assistance programs and has asked that we
                    discuss only loans with the Burmese at this time.</p>
                <p>In the light of Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HJB1">Hollister</persName>’s position
                    and the difficulties involved in obtaining Agriculture’s concurrence to the
                    token rice payment formula, it is suggested that Embassy Rangoon attempt to
                    negotiate loan agreements with Burma, leaving aside the question of grant aid
                    until Burma again raises the subject.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Recommendations:</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>That you approve the above courses of action.<note n="3" xml:id="d45fn3"
                            >No indication of approval appears on the source text.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>That you sign the telegram containing a personal message to Prime Minister
                            <persName corresp="#p_BS1">Ba Swe</persName> as a follow-up to the
                        communications between <persName corresp="#p_NU1">U Nu</persName> and
                        President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>. (Tab B)<note
                            n="4" xml:id="d45fn4">All three telegrams were signed by
                                <persName>Dulles</persName>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
